Comparing Bahrain against the other Gulf States, there are various measures and forecasts that can be used to determine the growth forecast, current account deficit, and a risk ranking. Qatar rates the highest on risk assessment in the group. However it has consistently held positive growth as % GDP compared to other states. Oman and Saudi Arabia both hold the same level of risk but lower than Bahrain. Oman, while consistently positive in its growth % GDP, its levels of growth has remained low between 2015 - 2017. 2015 has been the exception for its range at 4.2. Qatar has the lowest level of risk the group, however, the recent embargo on trade, diplomatic relations and trade relationships in the Gulf will influence growth negatively and increase risk depending on its debt/gdp levels. It also has a high current account deficit which could increase this year, perhaps into the next couple of years depending on relations with other Gulf states. Its growth forecast for 2017 is at 3.4.

Since this is a surprisingly big question I'm going to take the countries in order. Bahrain-In the last year all three ratings agencies have downgraded their outlook and Moody's cut their rating two weeks ago. I think it get's cut by an agency in the next year. Oman-All three agencies are negative and two have already cut their rating this year. I think it get's cut by an agency in the next year. Qatar-All three agencies are negative with Fitch and S&P extremely negative (negative watch) and one has already cut their rating this year. I think it extremely likely that it get's cut by an agency in the next year. Saudi Arabia-The outlook is stable for all three agencies, unless the political or economic situation deteriorates sharply I don't see a cut in the next year.

Saudi Arabia's oil IPO should keep them safe. The other three are small and dependent on oil but oil prices appear to be stabilizing. Qatar is the most likely one to slide further if their rift with the rest of the GCC continues.

Low oil prices and political instability, as the major determining factors, have dinged the credit scores of three of the four listed Gulf Council Cooperation states within the past month. Stability and earning power of the countries are questionable. Oil prices have stabilized at around $50 per barrel and besides US defense spending, a little banking and foreign aid packages, oil is their only major source of revenue and and oil profits have decreased significantly with no change in sight.
Oman should already have been downgraded and I will be surprised to not see it happen within a year.
